    <bioghist id="aspace_e2bb5e7b3a0002eede9771ce218b7cdf">
      <head>Historical Note</head>
      <p>El Andar magazine was a North American publication (based in Santa Cruz, California) started as a print magazine in 1989, that published Latino written and visual journalism. It has visual appeal, humor, photo essays, investigative journalism, poetry and short fiction, and satirical editorial cartoons. It transitioned to online-only publishing in 2000 until shutting down around 2010. The editorial and publishing team included Julia Reynolds, Jorge Chino, and Rachel Barron.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <processinfo id="aspace_54070597f2369a5cd74eebfb04b81a08">
      <head>Processing Information</head>
      <p>The collection is unprocessed, however is open for research with a box-level survey description.</p>
    </processinfo>
    <userestrict id="aspace_b159af64837acb67c956e3057a29f76a">
      <head>Restrictions</head>
      <p>While Special Collections is the owner of the physical and digital items, permission to examine collection materials is not an authorization to publish. These materials are made available for use in research, teaching, and private study. Any transmission or reproduction beyond that allowed by fair use requires permission from the owners of rights, heir(s) or assigns.</p>
    </userestrict>
    <prefercite id="aspace_8452934bafc7377f15d9f1396bde1789">
      <head>Preferred Citation</head>
      <p>[Identification of item], El Andar Magazine Records, M1802, Dept. of Special Collections, Stanford Libraries, Stanford, Calif.</p>
    </prefercite>
    <scopecontent id="aspace_afd72c939e6273473093485afdd3ac66">
      <head>Scope and Contents</head>
      <p>Includes business and administration files, editorial files, grants and funding proposals, research files, magazine issues, computer files,correspondence, photographs and other graphical files, and awards.</p>
    </scopecontent>
